{
    "analysis": "We ran metric-based fault identification for the five candidate services and found several short consecutive fault runs (length=2 minutes) across multiple services: ts-route-service (workload, latency-50), ts-auth-service (cpu, diskio, latency-50/90, mem), ts-travel-service (cpu), ts-train-service (latency-50/90), and ts-order-service (latency-50). Because multiple service-level faults were detected, we must use traces to localize the root-cause service: per the rules, the root cause is typically the most-downstream faulty service in the trace call chain. Note also that many trace groups have p95=0 for error_rate, so trace error_rate groups produce noisy/trivial anomalies — instead of thresholding error_rate by p95, we should identify actual non-zero error_rate occurrences and also look at duration_mean breaches relative to p95. Therefore the next step is to inspect traces for these metric-faulty services within the incident window to find non-zero error rates or duration anomalies and the earliest timestamps, which will let us determine the downstream faulty service and approximate failure reason (e.g., high latency vs socket errors).",
